#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "lut 3D"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Transform RGB values with a 3D LUT file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A 3D LUT is a tridimensional table that is used to transform a given RGB value into another RGB value. It is normally used for film simulation and color grading.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module accepts `.cube`, `.3dl`, `.png` (haldclut) and `.gmz` files. Uncompressed 3D LUT data is not saved in the database or the XMP file, but is instead saved to the 3D LUT file path inside the 3D LUT root folder. It is therefore important to back up your 3D LUT folder properly -- sharing an image with its XMP is pointless if the recipient doesn't also have the same 3D LUT file in their own 3D LUT folder.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The compressed format `.gmz` is only available when GMIC is installed. This format can hold a full library of LUTs, and LUT data loaded from this type of file _can_ be saved to the database and XMP files.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note**: the module clips all values outside of the range [0,1]. You may have to reduce the range of the input before applying.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "LUTs are most commonly used in darktable for color grading or film look simulation. For this reason, by default, the module is placed after the [_filmic rgb_](./filmic-rgb.md) module in the pixelpipe and should be applied to a neutral image (without first applying a specific look). While you can find hundreds of free LUTs on the internet, you should note that that not all of them are compatible with the darktable environment and workflow -- incompatible LUTs will not produce the advertised look. To limit the risk, a color grading LUT should have been created to work with one of the available \"application color spaces\" (see below), for both the input and the output of the module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Camera log LUTs (as F-log or S-Log3) are different to color-grading and film-look-simulation LUTs, and are intended to convert the camera log raw data into something (linear raw data or other color space) that darktable is able to understand. In this case the _lut 3D_ module should be manually placed between the [_demosaic_](./demosaic) and [_input color profile_](./input-color-profile.md) modules. Once you have done this, you can no longer choose an \"application color space\". The \"input profile\" of input color profile module should be aligned with the output of the LUT. _Please note that this use case has not yet been tested._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"file selection\n"
": Choose the 3D LUT file to use. File selection is inactive if the 3D LUT root folder has not been defined in [preferences > processing](../../preferences-settings/processing.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"application color space\n"
": A 3D LUT is defined relative to a specific color space. Choose the color space for which the selected 3D LUT file has been built. Cube files are usually related to REC.709 while most others are related to sRGB.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"interpolation\n"
": This defines how to calculate output colors when input colors are not exactly on a node of the RGB cube described by the 3D LUT. There are three interpolation methods available: tetrahedral (default), trilinear and pyramid. Usually you won't see any difference between interpolation methods except with smaller sized LUTs.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/monochrome.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "monochrome"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/monochrome.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Quickly convert an image to black & white using a variable color filter.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/monochrome.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "To use this module, first reduce the filter size (to concentrate its effect) and move it across the hue palette to find the best filter value for your desired image rendition. Then gradually expand the filter to include more hues and achieve more natural tonality.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/monochrome.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Although this module is easy to use, better results can usually be obtained by using the film emulation presets in the [_color calibration_](./color-calibration.md) module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/monochrome.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Under certain conditions, especially highly saturated blue light sources in the frame, this module may produce black pixel artifacts. Use the gamut clipping option of the [_input color profile_](./input-color-profile.md) module to mitigate this issue.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/monochrome.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"filter size/position\n"
": The default central location of the filter has a neutral effect but dragging it to an alternate position applies a filter analogous to taking a b&w photograph through a conventional color filter.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/monochrome.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": A color picker can be activated to automatically set the position and size of the filter based on the selected portion of the image. Scroll the mouse wheel to change the filter size, making the filter's range of hues more or less selective.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/monochrome.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"highlights\n"
": Control how much to retain highlights.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/shadows-and-highlights.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "shadows and highlights"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/shadows-and-highlights.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Modify the tonal range of the shadows and highlights of an image by enhancing local contrast.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/shadows-and-highlights.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_**Note:** This module performs blurs in Lab color space, which can result in a number of issues, including halos, high local contrast in highlights, and hue shifts towards blue in the shadows. Instead, use the [tone equalizer](./tone-equalizer.md) module instead._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/shadows-and-highlights.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shadows\n"
": Control the effect on shadows. Positive values will lighten shadows while negative values will darken them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/shadows-and-highlights.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"highlights\n"
": Control the effect on highlights. Positive values will lighten highlights while negative values will darken them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/shadows-and-highlights.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"white point adjustment\n"
": By default the algorithm of this module leaves the black and white points untouched. In some cases an image might contain tonal variations beyond the white point, i.e. above a luminance value of 100. A negative shift in the white point adjustment can bring these values back into the proper range so that further details in the highlights become visible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/shadows-and-highlights.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"soften with\n"
": The underlying blurring filter: gaussian or bilateral. Try the bilateral filter if the gaussian blur generates halos.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/shadows-and-highlights.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"radius\n"
": The radius of the blurring filter used by the algorithm. Higher values give softer transitions between shadows and highlights but might introduce halos. Lower values will reduce the size of halos but may lead to an artificial look. The bilateral filter is much less prone to halo artifacts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/shadows-and-highlights.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"compress\n"
": Control how strongly the effect extends to the mid-tones. High values limit the effect to only the extreme shadows and highlights. Lower values also cause adjustments to the mid-tones. At 100% this module has no visible effect as only absolute black and absolute white are affected.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/shadows-and-highlights.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shadows color adjustment\n"
": Control the color saturation adjustment made to shadows. High values cause saturation enhancements on lightened shadows. Low values cause desaturation on lightened shadows. It is normally safe to leave this at its default of 100%. This gives a natural saturation boost on shadows – similar to what you would expect in nature if shadows were to receive more light.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/shadows-and-highlights.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"highlights color adjustment\n"
": Control the color saturation adjustment made to highlights. High values cause saturation enhancements on darkened highlights. Low values cause desaturation on darkened highlights. Often highlights do not contain enough color information to give convincing colors when darkened. You might need to adjust this parameter in order to find the best fitting value depending on your specific image, but be aware that sometimes the results might not be fully satisfying.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "sharpen"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Sharpen the details in the image using a standard UnSharp Mask (USM). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module works by increasing the contrast around edges and thereby enhancing the _impression_ of sharpness of an image. This module is applied to the L channel in Lab color space.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_**Note:** The USM algorithm used in this module performs blurs in Lab color space, which can produce undesirable effects, and is no longer recommended. Instead use the presets offered by the [contrast equalizer](./contrast-equalizer.md) module for deblurring or the [local contrast](./local-contrast.md) module for general sharpness._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"radius\n"
": The unsharp mask applies a gaussian blur to the image as part of its algorithm. This parameter controls the radius of that blur which, in turn, defines the spatial extent of the edge enhancement. Very high values will lead to ugly over-sharpening.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"amount\n"
": The strength of the sharpening.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"threshold\n"
": Contrast differences below this threshold are excluded from sharpening. Use this to avoid amplification of noise.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/velvia.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "velvia"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/velvia.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Resaturate pixels in a weighted manner that gives more weight to blacks, whites and less saturated pixels. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/velvia.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_**Note:** This module causes hue and brightness shifts that can be difficult to manage. Instead, use the [color balance rgb](./color-balance-rgb.md) module for color modifications._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/velvia.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"strength\n"
": The strength of the effect\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/velvia.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mid-tones bias\n"
": Reduce the effect on mid-tones in order to avoid unnatural skin tones. Reducing the mid-tone bias decreases mid-tone protection and makes the overall velvia effect stronger.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "vignetting"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Apply a vignetting effect to the image. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Vignetting is a modification of the brightness and saturation at the borders of the image in a specified shape. Many of the parameters listed below can also be modified with a graphical control that overlays the image when the module has focus, showing the shape and extent of the effect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** This module is known to provoke banding artifacts under certain conditions. You should consider activating the [_dithering_](./dithering.md) module to alleviate this.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_**Also note:** This module can produce unnatural-looking results and should be used with care. Instead, use the [exposure](./exposure.md) module with an [elliptical mask](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) with a large transition area and, if necessary, use the [color balance rgb](./color-balance-rgb.md) module with the same mask to reduce saturation at the edges._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"scale\n"
": The radius of the vignetting area.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"fall-off strength\n"
": The progressiveness of the fall-off. Higher values cause a steeper transition.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"brightness\n"
": The intensity of brightening (positive values) or darkening (negative values).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"saturation\n"
": Control how strong colors become when desaturated/saturated in the darkened/brightened vignetting area.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"horizontal/vertical center\n"
": Shift the center of the vignetting area horizontally/vertically.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shape\n"
": The shape of the vignetting effect. The default value of 1 creates a circular or elliptical area. Smaller values shift the shape to being more square; higher values turn it into a cross-like shape.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"automatic ratio\n"
": Automatically adjust the width/height ratio of the vignetting area to match the aspect ratio of the underlying image. This typically causes the vignetting area to become elliptical.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"width/height ratio\n"
": Manually adjust the width/height ratio of the vignetting area.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vignetting.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"dithering\n"
": Activate random noise dithering to alleviate banding artifacts caused by vignette gradients. Select “8-bit output” to prevent banding on monitor display and for JPEGs. When set to “16-bit output”, only a small amount of dithering is applied, just strong enough to compensate for banding on the fine grained 16-bit level. It is now recommended that you instead use the [_dithering_](./dithering.md) module to alleviate banding artifacts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "basic adjustments (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.6 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [quick access panel](../../darkroom/organization/quick-access-panel.md) instead.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A convenience module that combines controls from [_exposure_](./exposure.md), [_highlight reconstruction_](./highlight-reconstruction.md), [_color balance_](./color-balance.md) and [_vibrance_](./vibrance.md) into a single module. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "While this module can provide a quick and convenient way to make simple adjustments to an image, it must be used with care. Normally exposure adjustments should come before [input color profile](./input-color-profile.md) in the pixelpipe, and color adjustments should come after. Because the _basic adjustments_ module combines all of these functions into a single operation in the pixelpipe, it may not play nicely with other modules. Therefore, if you plan to use _basic adjustments_ with other modules, please instead consider using the [_exposure_](exposure.md) + [_base curve_](base-curve.md) / [_tone curve_](tone-curve.md) / [filmic rgb](filmic-rgb.md) + [_color balance_](color-balance.md) modules so that these operations occur in the correct places in the pixelpipe.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"black level correction\n"
": Equivalent to black level correction in the [_exposure_](exposure.md) module, this slider defines the threshold at which dark gray values are cut off to pure black. Reducing this can bring some dark colors back into gamut. Increasing this slider may appear to increase the contrast and pop of an image, but it can push dark colors out of gamut, and clipped data cannot be recovered further down the pixel pipe. To control the contrast in the shadows, it is better to use other modules such as [_tone curve_](tone-curve.md) or [_levels_](levels.md), which mitigate these negative impacts further down the pixel pipeline.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"exposure\n"
": Adjust exposure compensation. Adding 1 EV of exposure compensation is equivalent to doubling the exposure time in camera, opening the aperture by 1 stop, or doubling the ISO. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": Positive exposure corrections will make the image brighter. As a side effect noise level is increased. Depending on the basic noise level of your camera and the ISO value of your image, positive exposure compensations with up to 1EV or 2EV should still give reasonable results.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": Negative exposure corrections will make the image darker. Given the nature of digital images this can not correct for fully blown out highlights but allows you to reconstruct data if only some of the RGB channels are clipped (see the [_highlight reconstruction_](highlight-reconstruction.md) module for information on how to deal with clipped pixels).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"highlight compression\n"
": Compress the highlights of the image in order to recover detail.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"contrast\n"
": Equivalent to the _contrast_ slider in the [_color balance_](color-balance.md) module, this is used to increase the separation of luminance values around a fulcrum point, in effect making the tone curve steeper. The _middle gray_ slider sets the fulcrum point for the contrast, and any pixels whose luminance matches this middle gray point will be unaffected. Pixels brighter than the middle gray point will become even brighter, and pixels darker than the middle gray point will become even darker.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"preserve colors\n"
": If a non-linear tone curve is applied to each of the RGB channels individually, then the amount of tone adjustment applied to each color channel may be different, and this can cause hue shifts. Therefore, the _preserve colors_ menu provides different methods of calculating the \"luminance level\" of a pixel. The amount of tone adjustment is calculated based on this luminance value, and then this same adjustment is applied to all three of the RGB channels. Different luminance estimators can affect the contrast in different parts of the image, depending on the specific characteristics of that image. The user can therefore choose a particular estimator that provides the best results for the given image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"middle gray\n"
": Set the fulcrum point for the _contrast_ slider. This is equivalent to the _contrast fulcrum_ slider on the [_color balance_](color-balance.md) module. If the contrast slider is set to 0 this slider will not have any effect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"brightness\n"
": Equivalent to increasing the _gamma factor_ slider in the [_color balance_](color-balance.md) module. Moving the slider to the right will increase the brightness of the image, with an emphasis on the mid-tones.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"saturation\n"
": Equivalent to the _output saturation_ slider on the [_color balance_](color-balance.md) module, this slider affects the saturation, or brilliance and intensity of the colors. Moving the slider to the right will increase the amount of color in the image; moving the slider to the left will reduce the amount of color in the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"vibrance\n"
": Accentuate the colors of the image without adding unnatural colors, as it's often the case with the _saturation_ slider. It works by reducing the lightness of already saturated pixels to make the colors more vivid. You can also achieve some interesting effects by combining it with the saturation slider to target more or less saturated areas of the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"auto\n"
": Automatically adjust the exposure, taking into account the entire image, or use the color picker to select a rectangular area of the image -- the exposure will be automatically adjusted based on the selected region. This allows you to prioritise which parts of the image should be well-exposed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/basic-adjustments.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"clip\n"
": This affects the number of pixels that will be clipped to black or white during the auto-exposure calculation. Moving this slider to the right will allow more pixels to be clipped and increase the contrast; moving this slider to the left will compress the image more and lower the contrast.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "channel mixer (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.4 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_color calibration_](./color-calibration.md) module instead.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A simple yet powerful tool to manage color channels.  \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module accepts red, green and blue channels as an input and provides red, green, blue, gray, hue, saturation and lightness channels as output. It allows you to independently control how much each input channel contributes to each output channel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "RGB matrix multiplication"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can think of the _channel mixer_ as a type of matrix multiplication between a 3x3 matrix and the input [R G B] values.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "set the destination to _red_ then set the Rr, Rg & Rb values using the red, green and blue sliders\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "set the destination to _green_ then set the Gr, Gg & Gb values using the red, green and blue sliders \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "set the destination to _blue_ then set the Br, Bg & Bb values using the red, green and blue sliders \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "By default, _channel mixer_ just copies the input [R G B] channels straight over to the matching output channels. This is equivalent to multiplying by the identity matrix:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "As an example use case, the following matrix is useful for taming ugly out-of-gamut blue LED lights by making them more magenta:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"┌  1.00  -0.18  0.18 ┐ \n"
"│ -0.20   1.00  0.20 │\n"
"└  0.05  -0.05  1.00 ┘ \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In this case it is useful to use a [parameteric mask](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md) to limit the effect of the _channel mixer_ to just the problematic colors.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A more intuitive take for what the _channel mixer_ sliders do:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "for the _red_ destination, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more red. Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more cyan.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "for the _green_ destination, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more green. Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more magenta.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "for the _blue_ destination, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more blue. Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more yellow.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Another very useful application of the _channel mixer_ is the ability to mix the channels together to produce a grayscale output -- a monochrome image. Use the _gray_ destination, and set the red, green and blue sliders to control how much each channel contributes to the brightness of the output. This is equivalent to the following matrix multiplication:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "When dealing with skin tones, the relative weights of the three channels will affect the level of detail in the image. Placing more weight on red (e.g. [0.9, 0.3, -0.3]) will make for smooth skin tones, whereas emphasising green (e.g. [0.4, 0.75, -0.15]) will bring out more detail. In both cases the blue channel is reduced to avoid emphasising unwanted skin texture.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Different types of traditional black and white film have differing sensitivities to red, green and blue colors, and this can be simulated by setting the gray destination coefficients appropriately. The _channel mixer_ module has a number of built-in presets that can be used to achieve this.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"destination\n"
": Select the destination channel that will be affected by the slider settings immediately below. The red, green and blue destination channels are used for color mixing as described in the _matrix multiplication_ section above. The gray channel is used for making grayscale images as described in the _monochome_ section above. It is also possible to define the R, G & B input channels to produce HSL (hue, saturation and lightness) values on the output, although this is a very specialised application.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"red\n"
": Defines how much the red input channel should contribute to the selected destination channel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"green\n"
": Defines how much the green input channel should contribute to the selected destination channel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blue\n"
": Defines how much the blue input channel should contribute to the selected destination channel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "defringe (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.6 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_chromatic aberrations_](./chromatic-aberrations.md) module instead.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Remove color fringing, which often results from Longitudinal Chromatic Aberrations (LCA), also known as Axial Chromatic Aberrations.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module uses edge-detection. Where pixels are detected as a fringe, the color is rebuilt from less saturated neighboring pixels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"operation mode\n"
": _global average_: This mode is is usually the fastest but might show slightly incorrect previews at high magnification. It might also protect the wrong regions of color too much or too little by comparison with local average.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": _local average_: This mode is slower because it computes local color references for every pixel. However it might protect color better than global average and allows for rebuilding color where actually required. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": _static threshold_: This mode does not use a color reference but directly uses the threshold as given by the user.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"edge detection radius\n"
": The algorithm uses the difference between the input image and a gaussian-blurred version of the same image to detect edges. This parameter controls the spatial extent of the gaussian blur used in the edge detection. Try increasing this value if you want a stronger detection of the fringes or the thickness of the fringe edges is too high.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"threshold\n"
": The threshold over which the edge of a pixel is counted as a “fringe”. Try lowering this value if there is not enough fringe detected and increasing it if too many pixels are desaturated.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "fill light (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.4 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_tone equalizer_](./tone-equalizer.md) module or the [_exposure_](./exposure.md) module with a [drawn mask](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md).**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Locally modify exposure based on pixel lightness.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module pushes exposure by increasing lightness with a Gaussian curve of a specified width, centered on a given lightness.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"exposure\n"
": The fill-light exposure (EV)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"center\n"
": The median lightness impacted by the fill-light. The lightness must be set manually but a color picker can be used to provide a guide based on a sample from the image. The lightness of the selected point/area is displayed in the gradient bar.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"width\n"
": The width of the Gaussian curve. This number is expressed in zones, with the full range being 10 zones.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "framing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Generate a frame around the image. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The frame consists of a border (with a user-defined color) and a frame line within that border (with a second user-defined color). Various options are available to control the geometry and color of the frame.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"border size\n"
": The size of the frame as a percentage of the underlying full image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid ""
#| "aspect ratio\n"
#| ": The aspect ratio of the image, including any cropping within darktable\n"
msgid ""
"aspect\n"
": The aspect ratio of the final module output (i.e. the underlying image plus the frame)\n"
msgstr ""
"bildproporcio\n"
": La bildproporcio de la bildo, inkluzive de ajna tondado en darktable\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"orientation\n"
": The orientation of the frame (portrait/landscape). Select 'auto' for darktable to choose the most reasonable orientation based on the underlying image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"horizontal/vertical position\n"
": Select from a set of pre-defined ratios to control where the underlying image will be positioned on the horizontal/vertical axis. You can also right click and enter your own ratio as \"x/y\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"frame line size\n"
": The percentage of the frame line size, relative to the border size at its smallest part.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"frame line offset\n"
": The position of the frame line, relative to the underlying image. Choose 0% for a frame line that touches the image. Choose 100% for a frame line that touches the outer border.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"border color / frame line color\n"
": A pair of color selectors which allow the border and frame line colors to be defined. Clicking on the colored field will open a color selector dialog which offers a choice of commonly-used colors, or allows you to define a color in RGB color space. You can also activate a color picker to take a color probe from the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/orientation.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/crop-rotate.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"show guides\n"
": Tick the box to show guide overlays whenever the module is activated. Click the icon on the right to control the properties of the guides. See [guides & overlays](../utility-modules/darkroom/guides-overlays.md) for details.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "global tonemap (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.4 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_filmic rgb_](./filmic-rgb.md) module instead.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Compress the tonal range of an HDR image into the limited tonal range of a typical LDR output file. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Global tonemap processes each pixel of an HDR image, without taking the local surrounding into account. This is generally faster than local [_tone mapping (deprecated)_](./tone-mapping.md), but might lead to less convincing results with very high-dynamic-range scenes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"operator\n"
": The operator to use. _Reinhard_, _Filmic_ and _Drago_ global tonemap operators are available. Depending on the selected operator, different parameters can be adjusted. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": Some operators are fully self-adjusting, and do not require specific controls.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"bias (_Drago_ operator only)\n"
": This parameter influences the contrast of the output image. It is an essential parameter for adjusting the compression of high values and the visibility of details in dark areas. A value of 0.85 is recommended as a starting point.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"target (_Drago_ operator only)\n"
": A scale factor to adjust the global image brightness to the brightness of the intended display. It is measured in cd/m, and should match the brightness of your output device. Higher values lead to a brighter image, while lower values lead to a darker image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"detail (all operators)\n"
": This parameter controls how much detail is preserved from the original input image and transferred back into the output image after tonemapping.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/invert.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "invert (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/invert.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.4 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_negadoctor_](./negadoctor.md) module instead.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/invert.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Invert scanned negatives.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/invert.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"color of film material\n"
": Clicking on the colored field will open a color selector dialog which offers you a choice of commonly used colors, or allows you to define an RGB color. You can also activate the color picker to take a color probe from your image – preferably from the unexposed border of your negative.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "lens correction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Automatically correct for (and simulate) lens distortion, transversal chromatic aberrations (TCA) and vignetting.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module identifies the camera/lens combination from the image's Exif data and uses the external [lensfun library](https://lensfun.github.io/) to provide correction parameters.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If your system's lensfun library has no correction profile for the automatically identified camera/lens combination, the controls for the three photometric parameters (below) are replaced with a warning message. You may try to find the right profile yourself by searching for it in the menu. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If your lens is present in the list but has not been correctly identified, this may require some adjustment within the exiv2 program (see [this post](https://dev.exiv2.org/boards/3/topics/2854) for details). Note that you may need to re-import the images once such adjustments have been made as the lens name is retrieved as part of the import process.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you can't find your lens, check if it is in the list of [currently supported lenses](https://lensfun.github.io/lenslist/), and try running the [`lensfun-update-data`](https://lensfun.github.io/manual/v0.3.2/lensfun-update-data.html) tool. If there is still no matching profile for your lens, a [lens calibration service](https://www.darktable.org/2013/07/have-your-lens-calibrated/) is offered by Torsten Bronger, one of darktable's users. Alternatively you may visit the [lensfun project](https://lensfun.github.io/lenslist/) to learn how to generate your own set of correction parameters. Don't forget to share your profile with the lensfun team!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"camera\n"
": The camera make and model as determined by the image's Exif data. You can override this manually and select your camera from a hierarchical menu. Only lenses with correction profiles matching the selected camera will be shown.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lens\n"
": The lens make and model as determined by the image's Exif data. You can override this manually and select your lens from a hierarchical menu. This is mainly required for pure mechanical lenses, but may also be needed for off-brand / third party lenses. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"photometric parameters (focal length, aperture, focal distance)\n"
": Lens corrections depend on certain photometric parameters that are read from the image's Exif data: focal length (for distortion, TCA, vignetting), aperture (for TCA, vignetting) and focal distance (for vignetting). Many cameras do not record focal distance in their Exif data, in which case you will need to set this manually.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": You can manually override all automatically selected parameters. Either take one of the predefined values from the drop-down menu or, with the drop-down menu still open, just type in your own value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"corrections\n"
": Choose which corrections (distortion, TCA, vignetting) darktable should apply. Change this from its default \"all\", if your camera has already performed some internal corrections (e.g. vignetting), or if you plan to undertake some corrections with a separate program.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"geometry\n"
": In addition to correcting lens flaws, this module can change the projection type of your image. Set this combobox to the desired projection type (e.g. \"rectilinear\", \"fish-eye\", \"panoramic\", \"equirectangular\", \"orthographic\", \"stereographic\", \"equisolid angle\", \"thoby fish-eye\").  To correct the aspect ratio of an anamorphic lens, use the [_rotate and perspective_](./rotate-perspective.md) module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"scale\n"
": Adjust the scaling factor of your image to avoid black corners. Press the auto scale button (to the right of the slider) for darktable to automatically find the best fit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mode\n"
": The default behavior of this module is to _correct_ lens flaws. Switch this combobox to \"distort\" in order to instead _simulate_ the flaws/distortions of a specific lens (inverted effect).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"TCA overwrite\n"
": Check this box to override the automatic correction parameters for TCA. This will expose the TCA red and TCA blue parameters below. Un-check the box to revert back to automatic corrections.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"TCA red; TCA blue\n"
": Override the correction parameters for TCA. You can also use these sliders to manually set the parameters if the lens profile does not include TCA correction. Look out for colored seams at features with high contrast edges and adjust the TCA parameters to minimize those seams.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"corrections done\n"
": Occasionally, for a given camera/lens combination, only some of the possible corrections are supported by lensfun's profiles. This message box will tell you which corrections have actually been applied to the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** TCA corrections will not be applied to images that have been identified as monochrome (see [developing monochrome images](../../guides-tutorials/monochrome.md) for more information).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** The lens correction module will fill in missing data at the borders by repeating the borders' pixels. For strong corrections, this filling can be visible (especially on noisy images). Crop the image if necessary.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "liquify"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Move pixels around by applying freestyle distortions to parts of the image using points, lines and curves.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Each of liquify's tools is based on nodes. A point consists of a single node and a line or curve consists of a sequence of linked nodes defining a path.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Each instance of the liquify module is limited to a maximum of 100 nodes -- for more nodes, use additional instances. However, please note that the liquify module consumes a lot of system resources. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Drag the central point of a node to move the node around. The radius describes the area of the effect (distortion occurs only within this radius). To change the radius drag the handle at the circumference. A strength vector starting from the center describes the direction of the distortion, and its strength is depicted by the length of the vector. Change the vector by dragging its arrow head. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "points"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A point consists of a single node and strength vector. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Click the point icon to activate the point tool and then click on the image to place it. Hold Ctrl while clicking on the point icon to add multiple points without having to click the icon again each time. Right-click to exit creation mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "point modes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The strength vector of a point has three different modes. These can be toggled by holding Ctrl and clicking on the arrowhead of the strength vector.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"linear\n"
": A linear distortion inside the circle, starting from the opposite side of the strength vector and following the vector's direction. This is the default mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": ![linear](./liquify/liquify_ex1.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"radial growing\n"
": The strength vector's effect is radial, starting with a strength of 0% in the center and increasing away from the center. This mode is depicted by an additional circle with the arrow pointing outwards.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": ![radial growing](./liquify/liquify_ex4.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"radial shrinking\n"
": The strength vector's effect is radial, starting with a strength of 100% in the center and decreasing away from the center. This mode is depicted by an additional circle with the arrow pointing inwards.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": ![radial shrinking](./liquify/liquify_ex3.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "feathering"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"default mode\n"
": By default the strength varies linearly from 0% to 100% between the center and the radius of the control point. It is possible to modify the feathering effect by clicking on the center of the circle.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": ![default](./liquify/liquify_ex1.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"feathered mode\n"
": In \"feathered\" mode, two control circles are displayed, which can be modified independently to feather the strength of the effect. Note that clicking the center of the circle again hides the feathering controls but does _not_ return to the default mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": ![feathered](./liquify/liquify_ex2.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "removing points"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A point can be removed by right-clicking on the center of the node.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "lines and curves"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Lines and curves are sequences of points linked together by straight or curved lines. The effect is interpolated by a set of associated strength vectors. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Click the appropriate icon to activate the line or curve tool and then click on the image to place a sequence of points forming the path. Right-click anywhere when the last point has been placed in order to finish drawing the line/curve.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Hold Ctrl while clicking on the line/curve icon to add multiple lines/curves without having to click the icon again each time. Right-click a second time to exit creation mode after the final line or curve has been completed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lines\n"
": ![lines](./liquify/liquify_ex5.png#w50)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"curves\n"
": ![curves](./liquify/liquify_ex6.png#w50)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Ctrl+click on a line or curve segment to add a new control point. Ctrl+right-click on the center of a node to remove a control point. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Right-click on a segment to remove the shape completely. Ctrl+Alt+click on a segment to change that segment from a line to a curve and vice versa.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "link modes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Ctrl+click on the center of a node to change the way the points of a curve are linked together. There are four modes, which correspond to different ways of handling the steepness of the bezier curve using control handles: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"autosmooth\n"
": This is the default mode, in which control handles are not displayed -- controls are automatically computed to give a smooth curve.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
